---
import Chapter from "@/layouts/Chapter.astro";
import Heading from "@/components/Articles/Heading.astro";
import Prose from "@/components/Articles/Prose.astro";
import Keyword from "@/components/Articles/Keyword.astro";
import Lexer from "@/components/Animations/Lexer/Lexer";
import LexerTokens from "./_components/LexerTokens";
import LexerInitialization from "./_components/LexerInitialization.astro";
import LexerHelpers from "./_components/LexerHelpers.astro";
import LexerNext from "./_components/LexerNext.astro";
import LexerNextToken from "./_components/LexerNextToken.astro";
import NextTokenLetters from "./_components/NextTokenLetters.astro";
import HandlingLetters from "./_components/HandlingLetters.astro";
import LookupIdentDefinition from "./_components/LookupIdentDefinition.astro";
import LexerExercise from "./_components/LexerExercise.astro";
import LinkContainer from "@/components/Articles/Links/LinkContainer.astro";
---

<Chapter title="Understanding the Lexer Mechanics">
  <Heading>Understanding the Lexer Mechanics</Heading>
  <Prose>
    <p>
      Think of the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> — also called a <Keyword
        word="Tokenizer"
      /> — as <strong>your eyes</strong>
      reading through a page. If you read the phrase <strong
        >"Redis is fast"</strong
      >, you don't think of it as 13 characters and spaces. Instead, you
      instantly group those characters into three distinct concepts: <strong
        >[Redis]</strong
      >, <strong>[is]</strong>, and <strong>[fast]</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>Let's see how it operates with our classic example command:</p>

    <Lexer commandKind="SET" command="SET username Alejandro" client:only />

    <p>
      This animation represents the process of turning a <strong
        >raw string</strong
      > into a <strong>meaningful representation</strong>. In computer science,
      this process is known as <strong>Lexical Analysis</strong> — or simply lexing.
      A <Keyword word="Lexer" /> performs this exact task for our Commands: it takes
      a raw Command string and transforms it into an organized <Keyword
        word="[]Token"
      />.
    </p>

    <LexerTokens command="SET username Alejandro" client:load />

    <p>
      To <strong>navigate through</strong> the input efficiently, our <Keyword
        word="Lexer"
      /> tracks its internal state using three fields:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="pos" />: The index of the character we are currently
        examining.
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="readPos" />: Our look-ahead pointer — always one step
        ahead of <Keyword word="pos" />, crucial for detecting multi-byte
        sequences like <Keyword word="\\r\\n" /> (which will be seen on the <strong
          >Redis Serialization Protocol chapter</strong
        >).
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="ch" />: The current character being examined at <Keyword
          word="readPos"
        />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Putting it all together, here is how our <Keyword word="Lexer" /> is defined
      in <strong>Go</strong>:
    </p>

    <LexerInitialization />

    <p>
      Before <strong>Lexing</strong>, we need to sanitize the <Keyword
        word="input"
      /> and initialize our <Keyword word="pointers" />. Two functions handle
      this:
    </p>

    <LexerHelpers />

    <ol>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="trimInput()" />: Removes <strong
          >trailing whitespace</strong
        > from the right of the command, preventing the <Keyword word="Lexer" />
        from processing ghost characters at the end of a line.
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="New()" />: Initializes the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> with our
        sanitized input and zeroed pointers. It immediately calls <Keyword
          word="next()"
        /> — a function that <strong>advances the pointers</strong> and loads the
        current character into <Keyword word="ch" /> — so that by the time the caller
        receives the <Keyword word="Lexer" />, it is already positioned and
        ready to scan.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>Now let's look at what <Keyword word="next()" /> actually does:</p>

    <LexerNext />

    <p>
      <Keyword word="next()" /> drives character-by-character advancement through
      the input. It handles two cases:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>End of File (EOF):</strong> If <Keyword word="readPos" /> exceeds
        the <strong>length of the input</strong>, <Keyword word="ch" /> is set to
        <Keyword word="token.EOF" />, signaling that the input has been fully
        consumed.
      </li>

      <li>
        <strong>Advancing:</strong> Otherwise, <Keyword word="ch" /> is updated to
        the character at <Keyword word="readPos" />. Then <Keyword word="pos" />
        catches up to <Keyword word="readPos" />, and <Keyword word="readPos" />
        increments to scout the <strong>next character.</strong>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Now that we have implemented <Keyword word="next()" />, we need to
      implement <Keyword word="NextToken()" /> — whose purpose is to scan the input
      and return the <Keyword word="Token" /> we defined in the
      <a href="/projects/redis/token" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
        previous chapter</a
      >. We will build it incrementally, starting with the two most fundamental
      cases any <Keyword word="Lexer" /> must handle before anything else: knowing
      <strong>when to stop</strong> and knowing <strong>what to ignore.</strong>
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>EOF</strong> — <Keyword word="token.EOF" /> has the value <Keyword
          word="0"
        />, known as the <strong>null terminator</strong> in ASCII. When <Keyword
          word="l.ch"
        /> equals <Keyword word="token.EOF" />, the input has been fully
        consumed and we return a Token with Kind set to token.EOF.
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="Whitespace" /> — <Keyword word="skipWhitespaces()" /> advances
        the pointers past any <strong>spaces, tabs, or newlines</strong> so that
        <Keyword word="readPos" /> is always positioned on a meaningful character
        when we begin scanning a new <Keyword word="Token" />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <LexerNextToken />

    <p>
      With our two fundamental cases handled, our <Keyword word="NextToken()" />
      is now ready to tackle the <strong>core scanning logic.</strong> There are
      two kinds of values our <Keyword word="Lexer" /> needs to be able to read:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Letters</strong> — for commands like <Keyword word="SET" /> and identifiers
        like <Keyword word="userName" />.
      </li>

      <li>
        <strong>Numbers</strong> — for numeric values like <Keyword
          word="100"
        /> or <Keyword word="20" />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>Let's start with letters.</p>

    <NextTokenLetters />

    <p>Two utility functions handle letter scanning:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="isLetter()" /> — defines what constitutes a <strong
          >valid character</strong
        >
        in our <Keyword word="Lexer" />. Notice that it includes the <strong
          >underscore</strong
        >
        <Keyword word="_" />, allowing identifiers like <Keyword
          word="author_name"
        /> to be recognized as a single token.
      </li>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="readIdent()" /> — advances through the input for as long as
        <Keyword word="isLetter()" /> returns <strong>true</strong>, then
        extracts the scanned word using <Keyword word="input[pos:l.pos]" />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Now let's see how <Keyword word="readIdent()" /> plugs into <Keyword
        word="NextToken()"
      />:
    </p>

    <HandlingLetters />

    <p>
      Once <Keyword word="skipWhitespaces()" /> has positioned us on a meaningful
      character, we check if it is a letter. If so, two things happen:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        We use <Keyword word="readIdent()" /> to extract the full word as a Literal.
      </li>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="token.LookupIdent()" /> examines that <Keyword
          word="Literal"
        /> and determines its <Keyword word="Kind" /> — whether it is a known command
        like <Keyword word="SET" />, or a <strong>user-defined</strong> identifier
        like <Keyword word="userName" />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      The <Keyword word="Token" /> is then returned immediately, without the <Keyword
        word="Lexer"
      />
      advancing any further. The next call to <Keyword word="NextToken()" /> will
      pick up exactly where <strong>we left off</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      But we haven't implemented <Keyword word="token.LookupIdent()" /> yet — let's
      do that now.
    </p>

    <LookupIdentDefinition />

    <p>
      <Keyword word="LookupIdent()" /> consults a lookup table that associates every
      known Redis command with its corresponding <Keyword word="TokenKind" />:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        If the word is a known command — for example <Keyword word={`"SET"`} />
        returns <Keyword word="SET" /> — its specific <Keyword
          word="TokenKind"
        /> is returned.
      </li>
      <li>If not, it falls back to <Keyword word="IDENT" />.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      With this design adding support for a <strong>new Redis command</strong> is
      as simple as adding a single entry to the <Keyword word="keywords" /> map.
    </p>

    <h3 class="fraunces">Putting it all Together</h3>

    <p>
      Now that our <Keyword word="Lexer" /> knows how to identify both <strong
        >commands</strong
      > and
      <strong>identifiers</strong>, let's see it in action with a new command:
    </p>

    <Lexer commandKind="INCRBY" command="INCRBY rewrites 3" client:only />

    <p>
      Notice how the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> correctly identifies <Keyword
        word="INCRBY"
      /> as a command token, <Keyword word="articleRewrites" /> as an <strong
        >identifier</strong
      >, and <Keyword word="1" /> as a <strong>number</strong> — exactly the token
      kinds we have been building toward.
    </p>
  </Prose>

  <LexerExercise />

  <LinkContainer prevSection="token" nextSection="lexer-implementation" />
</Chapter>
